x86_64

================================================

This repo demonstrates systems programming on x86_64 Linux.
It combines C for logic and I/O with assembly for low-level operations
and performance-critical code.

The codebase includes a linked list data structure with both C and assembly
implementation. All modules follow x86_64 calling conventions and ABI standards,
showing how modern systems software integrates compiled and assembled code.
Current examples cover linked list operations (push, append, delete, find, length)
and SIMD vector operations for high-performance computing.
since it is just only beginning it doesn't contain huge codebase.
It is only a **initail** structure...

Building "make" Running "./program" [use this commands].

Cleaning "make clean" [to clean build artifacts].

"The build system automatically *compiles* all C sources and *assembles* all
architecture-specific code, *linking* them into a *single* executable."

------------

Architecture

The project is organized into *distinct* modules. Linked list functionality is provided in
both C and hand-optimized assembly.
[single instructions processes multiple data elements] SIMD [like an array but not like that] 
operations demonstrate vector processing capabilities.
All assembly code uses position-independent addressing and proper stack frames.

This serves as a reference implementation for systems-level programming on
x86_64, demonstrating register usage, calling conventions, and data structure
implementation in both C and assembly [Like all project maintained].

